q5XIcGoxEVftDfPD0X8DdvJ8%3D" id="w1_5_6_11_15_16"><mxCell style="rounded=1;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fontSize=11;fillColor=#c9b3dd;strokeColor=#4a2a78;fontColor=#201040;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="866" y="813" width="244" height="140" as="geometry"/></mxCell></object><object label="Person-affecting&lt;br&gt;view&lt;br&gt;[1+5+6+11+15+16+17]&lt;br&gt;→ AI safety (Redwood Research)&lt;br&gt;   0.43 lives-eq/$1k · 3% best&lt;br&gt;   runner-up GiveWell top charity (AMF) · 67%&lt;br&gt;(Jan Narveson, Melinda Roberts)" tooltip="&lt;b&gt;parochial + far_away_humans + future_humans_matter_with_discounting + no_discounting_future_humans + resilience_undermines_deterrence + space_expansion_backfires + living_in_simulation + person_affecting_view&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Person-affecting population ethics: making happy people is neutral, so the astronomical case for x-risk reduction — which rests on the sheer number of extra future lives saved from extinction — loses almost all its force. Only the harm to people who exist regardless still counts. This is the standard premise longtermism&#x27;s critics deny (discussed as the key objection in Greaves &amp; MacAskill&#x27;s &#x27;The Case for Strong Longtermism&#x27;). It requires no_discounting_future_humans, the astronomical-stakes move it pushes back on. || Chain: 0 parochial → 1 far_away_humans → 5 future_humans_matter_with_discounting → 6 no_discounting_future_humans → 11 resilience_undermines_deterrence → 15 space_expansion_backfires → 16 living_in_simulation → 17 person_affecting_view" link="https://www.squiggle-language.com/playground#code=eJy1WW1v2sgW%2FitH0d17IQvE5jWQm5XShOxWN%2B1GSapq1VR0sAeYje3xnbFDaLf97feZsQ0mgRsktF8qao%2FPec5z3iffDnw%2BYWmQnEufHwwOjo7o9PSU7hQTESWSPMW%2BLvBjHtF92nTcNs2lCvxHwec0d0edUXfkuiO3M3Lxo0cVnciY3F7VSLmPIO1M6zSMEyEj8mYQOiCHYqakNxMsMDLdfpNcmjA1YnO2GM3SkEW6eNGhSZqkiuePRyFLEq5Gc5HMRr7QnkyjRETT4niXIll%2BPlr7eqnNJcW1CASPPD5KI5%2BrUERcj3wO4co8XR7tkI4ZTvGnGBJgxWjMvIeJgIDlmS4F4tFoE9FIizANmD